# # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# # STAGE 4 · runner  (the actual production image)
# #
# # PURPOSE: Run the Next.js app with the absolute minimum footprint.
# #
# # With output: 'standalone', Next.js creates three things we need:
# #
# #   .next/standalone/      → A self-contained Node.js server. Includes server.js
# #                            and a minimal node_modules with only runtime deps.
# #                            No TypeScript, no build tools, no source files.
# #
# #   .next/static/          → Compiled client-side JS/CSS chunks, fonts, etc.
# #                            Must be placed at .next/static relative to where
# #                            server.js expects to find it.
# #
# #   public/                → Static assets (favicon, images, robots.txt, etc.)
# #
# # That is all. We do NOT need package.json, pnpm, or node_modules in this stage.
# # The standalone server already has its own minimal node_modules baked in.
# #
# # HOSTNAME=0.0.0.0 is required. By default Node.js servers bind to 127.0.0.1
# # (localhost). Inside a container, localhost is the container's own loopback —
# # traffic from outside the container (the host, other containers, a load
# # balancer) cannot reach it. 0.0.0.0 means "accept connections on all
# # network interfaces", which is what you need in a container.
# # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
